Part I - Ford GoBike System Data¶

by Hassani Imane¶

Introduction¶

The Ford GoBike System Data is a rich dataset that contains information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system that covers the greater San Francisco Bay area. This dataset is valuable for both exploratory and explanatory visualizations. In this work, we will explore different ways to visualize this dataset and highlight some of the insights that can be gained from it.

Preliminary Wrangling¶

In this section, I will examine the dataset's general characteristics to eliminate any null values and duplicates. I will also convert certain columns to more appropriate types, remove any unnecessary columns, and create new columns that I will utilize. i will start by upgrading a package

# change bike_share_for_all_trip and user_type and member_gender datatype into category

df_bike.member_gender = df_bike.member_gender.astype('category')
df_bike.bike_share_for_all_trip = df_bike.bike_share_for_all_trip.astype('category')

# change ids from float64 to object (str)
df_bike.start_station_id = df_bike.start_station_id.astype(object)
df_bike.end_station_id = df_bike.end_station_id.astype(object)
df_bike.bike_id = df_bike.bike_id.astype(object)

# change member_birth_year from float64 to int
df_bike.member_birth_year = df_bike.member_birth_year.astype(int)

#change start_time and end_time types from object to datetime
df_bike.start_time = pd.to_datetime(df_bike.start_time)
df_bike.end_time = pd.to_datetime(df_bike.end_time)

# Function convert second into day hours, minutes and seconds
def ConvSecToPeriod(x):
  
    day = x // (24 * 3600)
  
    x = x % (24 * 3600)
    hour = x // 3600
  
    x %= 3600
    minute = x // 60
  
    x %= 60
    second = x
      
    print(day,"days", hour, "hours", 
          minute, "minutes",
          second, "seconds")

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Ford GoBike System dataset contains information on bike trips taken using the Ford GoBike bike-sharing system in the San Francisco Bay Area. The data covers the period of feb 2019 with 183412 row and 16 columns, it includes information such as the start and end time of the trip, the start and end stations, the duration of the trip, and the user type (either a subscriber or a customer). Additionally, some demographic information about the users is available, including their age, gender, and the bike they used

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main features of interest in the Ford GoBike System dataset are related to the characteristics of the bike trips taken using the Ford GoBike bike-sharing system in the San Francisco Bay Area. Some of the key features of interest in the dataset include:

Trip duration: This feature represents the amount of time that a user spends on a bike trip. This is an important feature as it can provide insights into the preferences of users for trip length, which can help bike-sharing systems to optimize their offerings.

Start and end stations: These features represent the location where a user started and ended their bike trip. This can provide valuable information on the most popular trip routes, and can help bike-sharing systems to optimize their station locations to meet user demand.

User type: This feature represents the type of user, either a subscriber or a customer. This can provide insights into the different usage patterns of different user types, and can help bike-sharing systems to tailor their offerings to meet the needs of different user segments.

Demographic information: The dataset includes some demographic information about the users, including their age and gender. This information can provide insights into the characteristics of different user segments, and can help bike-sharing systems to tailor their offerings to meet the needs of different user groups.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

In addition to the previous features, other features such as the time and day of the week that trips were taken, the sharing bike system, and the bike used, may also be helpful in investigating usage patterns and optimizing bike-sharing offerings.

#The interquartile range (IQR) is a measure of variability or dispersion in a dataset
#The IQR is commonly used in statistics to identify outliers in a dataset. 
#Outliers are typically defined as values that fall outside of the range
#defined by Q1 - 1.5 * IQR and Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

# Calculate the IQR for the 'duration_sec' column
Q1 = df_bike['duration_sec'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df_bike['duration_sec'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

# Calculate the upper and lower bounds for outlier detection
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR
lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR

# Remove outliers from the 'age' column
df_filtered = df_bike[(df_bike['duration_sec'] >= lower_bound) & (df_bike['duration_sec'] <= upper_bound)]

# Calculate the maximum age in the filtered DataFrame
max_duration = np.max(df_filtered['duration_sec'])
# Calculate the maximum age in the filtered DataFrame
min_duration = np.min(df_filtered['duration_sec'])

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The dataset contains various variables of interest, including user type, gender, age, trip duration... Here's a brief discussion of the distributions of these variables:

User Type: The majority of users were subscribers, with more than 9 times the number of customers. This is not unusual for a bike-sharing system, as subscribers tend to use the system more frequently.

Gender: The majority of users were males, approximately three times more than females. This is a common pattern observed in bike-sharing systems.

Age: The bike-sharing system is used by users of different ages, but it is more concentrated among users between 25 and 40 years old, which represents approximately 50%. There were some unusual points in the age distribution, such as some members having an age of over 100 years, which is unlikely. We addressed this issue by removing the outliers in the member age variable to improve the quality of our analysis.

Trip Duration: The distribution of the trip duration had a long tail, with some trips lasting several hours, which is unusual for a bike-sharing system. Therefore, we decided to remove the outliers in the trip duration variable to make the distribution more normal and facilitate our analysis.

In general, the distributions of the variables of interest were generally consistent with what one would expect for a bike-sharing system in a city like San Francisco. However, there were some unusual points in the age and trip duration distributions, which we addressed by removing outliers to improve the quality of our analysis.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Yes, there were some unusual distributions that I observed during the data investigation. For example, the majority of the duration trip values were less than 1500 seconds. Additionally, the age distribution of the users was more concentrated among users between 25 and 40 years old.

To tidy and adjust the data, I performed several operations on it. I changed the data type of some features, such as bike_share_for_all_trip, user_type, member_gender, start_station_id, end_station_id, and bike_id, to category and string types to improve memory usage and make the data more manageable.

I also created new columns, such as start_day, start_hour, and member_age, to help better understand the patterns in the data. The start_day and start_hour columns were created to investigate the trend in the usage of the bike-sharing system throughout the day and week. The member_age column was created to provide more insights into the age distribution of the users.

Furthermore, I dropped some columns, such as start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_latitude, and end_station_longitude, that I deemed unnecessary for the analysis. Finally, I replaced the member_birth_year column with the member_age column for better understanding of the data.

All these transformations were necessary to obtain a clean and tidy dataset, which is crucial for effective data analysis.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Subscribed members take a higher number of rides during weekdays compared to weekends. This trend is consistent across all genders. In contrast, the number of customer riders is significantly lower than that of subscribed riders and looks uniform across all weekdays. This suggests that customers may be using the bike-sharing service more for leisure or recreational purposes, while subscribers may be using it more for practical purposes like commuting to work.

Male riders take a higher number of rides than female riders, and this trend is consistent across all membership types. Additionally, male riders take a higher number of rides during peak hours, specifically between 7-9 AM and 4-6 PM. This suggests that men may be more likely to use the bike-sharing service for commuting to work or other daily activities.

Non-bike sharing for all trips riders take a higher number of rides during working days, specifically between 7-9 AM and 4-6 PM, while the number of bike sharing for all trips riders looks relatively uniform across all weekdays. This indicates that the bike sharing for all trips option may be more attractive to non-working day riders or those who use the service for leisure purposes.

Most customers have a relatively longer trip duration compared to subscribers, suggesting that customers may be using the bike-sharing service for longer, more leisurely trips.

There are more younger riders on the weekends compared to other weekdays, and the age group of 20 to 40 years is the most common among riders during working days. This indicates that the age demographic of bike-sharing service users may vary depending on the day of the week.

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

The number of male subscribers is significantly higher than that of female subscribers, while the number of male customers is only slightly higher than that of female customers. This suggests that there may be a gender gap in the usage of bike-sharing services, with men more likely to be subscribers and women more likely to be customers.

The age distribution of bike-sharing service users is generally skewed towards younger riders, with the majority of riders falling in the 20 to 40 years age group. However, there are some outliers with maximum ages of around 120 to 140 years. This suggests that bike-sharing services are primarily used by younger riders, but there may be some older riders who use the service as well.

The duration of trips per gender and per bike sharing option are almost similar, indicating that the duration of trips is not strongly influenced by gender or membership type.

The majority of bike sharing for all trips users are younger than non-bike sharing for all trips users, suggesting that the bike sharing for all trips option may be more attractive to younger riders.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Conclusions¶

The main findings from the data exploration of Ford GoBike System Data are:

  • The majority of bike trips were taken by males, with females and other genders accounting for a smaller percentage of total trips.

  • The highest number of trips occurred during the weekdays, with peak usage times during the morning and evening commute hours.

  • The average trip duration was approximately 10-15 minutes, with a few outliers that lasted much longer.

  • The most popular start and end stations were concentrated in downtown San Francisco, with a few other popular stations scattered throughout the city.

  • There were some instances of missing data or outliers that required cleaning and further investigation.

During the data exploration process, several steps were taken to gain a better understanding of the data and uncover these findings. These steps included:

  • Cleaning the data by removing null values and outliers.

  • Creating visualizations, such as histograms and violin plots, to explore the distribution of variables and identify patterns.

  • Calculating summary statistics, such as mean, median, and mode, to understand the central tendency and variability of variables.

  • Grouping data by various categories, such as gender and time of day, to identify trends and patterns.

  • Conducting further investigation into instances of missing data or outliers to ensure the accuracy of the analysis.

The data exploration process was thorough and effective in uncovering important insights about the Ford GoBike System Data. The steps taken provided a comprehensive view of the data and allowed for a deeper understanding of user behavior and system usage patterns.
